$string['detail_rationale_balance'] = 'Dawson (2006) classified LMS tools into four functional categories and found that the pattern of tool usage — not just the volume — was predictive of learning outcomes. Courses where students predominantly consume content passively, without engaging in peer interaction or assessment, produce weaker learning outcomes. Macfadyen & Dawson (2012) extended this finding, showing that discussion-related activities (both posting and reading) were among the strongest predictors of final grade. An imbalanced activity profile where engagement is near zero suggests the course design may not be providing sufficient interactive learning opportunities, or that students are not finding their way to engagement activities.';
$string['detail_rationale_compound'] = 'Research in online learning consistently identifies the combination of social isolation and academic failure as the strongest predictor of student withdrawal. Bawa\'s (2016) review of retention in online courses found that social disconnection and academic underperformance together drive attrition rates 10–20% higher than in traditional settings. Muljana & Luo\'s (2019) systematic review of 40 studies confirmed that student engagement, sense of belonging, and instructional facilitation are the most prominent factors affecting online retention — and that their combined absence is the most reliable predictor of dropout. The Community of Inquiry framework further emphasises that academic success depends on social integration. When a student is both disconnected from peers and failing academically, they lack both the social support network and the academic momentum to self-correct. These students require the most urgent, individualised intervention.';
$string['detail_rationale_engagement'] = 'Cognitive presence — the extent to which learners construct meaning through sustained reflection and discourse — is a core pillar of the Community of Inquiry framework. Low engagement with course activities signals that students are not progressing through the inquiry cycle (triggering event → exploration → integration → resolution). Research by Garrison & Cleveland-Innes (2005) demonstrates that passive consumption of content does not produce deep learning; active engagement with activities is required.';
$string['detail_rationale_failing'] = 'A high failure rate across a cohort is a systemic signal, not merely an individual student issue. It may indicate misaligned assessment expectations, insufficient scaffolding, or a gap between the assumed and actual prior knowledge of the cohort. Research by Yorke (2003) on first-year student retention shows that early academic failure, especially when widespread, erodes student self-efficacy and significantly increases dropout risk.';
$string['detail_rationale_feedback'] = 'Teaching presence — the design, facilitation, and direction of cognitive and social processes — relies on a complete feedback loop. When students do not review teacher feedback, they miss targeted guidance on how to improve. Hattie & Timperley (2007) found that feedback is among the most powerful influences on learning, but only when it is received and acted upon. An unreviewed feedback item represents a broken loop in the teaching-learning cycle.';
$string['detail_rationale_isolation'] = 'Social presence is a foundational pillar of the Community of Inquiry framework. Students who do not participate in course discussions miss opportunities for collaborative knowledge construction, peer support, and the social bonds that sustain motivation in online learning. Research by Garrison, Anderson & Archer (2000) demonstrates that social presence is a prerequisite for meaningful cognitive engagement. Rovai (2002) found that a sense of community is one of the strongest predictors of student persistence in online courses.';
$string['detail_rationale_stale'] = 'Students who were previously active but have stopped participating represent a distinct risk profile from those who never engaged. A sudden drop in activity often signals a change in circumstances — personal issues, workload problems, loss of motivation, or difficulty with course content. Research on early warning systems in online learning (Macfadyen & Dawson, 2010) shows that declining activity patterns are among the most reliable predictors of course failure or withdrawal.';
$string['detail_student_method_consistency'] = 'Consistency is measured by calculating the standard deviation of the time gaps between consecutive submissions, normalised against the total course span. A perfectly even spread scores 100%; highly clustered submissions score near 0%. Only graded submissions with timestamps are included.';
$string['detail_student_method_engagement'] = 'Course engagement is measured by counting how many distinct trackable activities this student has interacted with. Activities include: assignments submitted and graded, quiz attempts completed, and resources viewed (pages, books, files, URLs, folders — tracked via Moodle\'s log store). The engagement rate is the proportion of total trackable course activities the student has engaged with.';
$string['detail_student_method_feedback'] = 'For this student, we count the number of graded assignments where a teacher has provided a grade, then check Moodle\'s log store for events indicating the student viewed their feedback (feedback_viewed or submission_status_viewed events). The review rate is the proportion of graded items for which this student has viewed the feedback.';
$string['detail_student_method_isolation'] = 'Social isolation is assessed by combining two COI social presence widgets: Community Engagement (forum posts, discussions started, collaborative contributions) and Peer Connection (replies to other students\' posts, workshop peer assessments). Each widget uses the student\'s participation rate — the proportion of course discussion threads they have contributed to. Students at "Not started" or "Emerging" on either widget are flagged. Recency is also checked: if the student was previously active but has not posted in 14+ days, they are flagged as "stale".';
$string['detail_student_method_selfregulation'] = 'Self-regulation is measured using a composite of four indicators, each drawn from Moodle\'s log store and assignment data: (1) Progress monitoring (40% weight) — how frequently the student checks their grades, measured as grade report views per week (2 views/week = 100%); (2) Feedback utilisation (25%) — the proportion of graded items for which the student has viewed teacher feedback; (3) Resource revisiting (20%) — distinct days per week the student accesses course materials (3 days/week = 100%); (4) Planning behaviour (15%) — the proportion of assignments viewed before the submission date. These four scores are weighted and combined into a composite percentage. A minimum of 2 weeks of enrolment is required for the metric to activate.';
$string['detail_student_method_streak'] = 'The pass streak tracks consecutive graded assessments where this student met or exceeded the 50% pass threshold. A "broken streak" is flagged when the student had a streak of 2+ passes and then received a grade below 50%. The consistency widget is cross-referenced to check whether the student is also submitting work in uneven bursts, which may indicate cramming rather than sustained engagement.';
$string['detail_student_method_timing'] = 'Submission timing is calculated from the difference between each assignment\'s due date and the student\'s actual submission timestamp. Early submissions receive a positive offset, late submissions receive a negative offset. The average offset across all submissions determines the overall rating: "ahead" (consistently early), "on track" (small buffer), "close" (cutting it fine), or "behind" (mostly late). The consistency widget is cross-referenced to check for clustered submission patterns.';
$string['detail_student_method_trend'] = 'The trend is calculated by examining this student\'s most recent graded assessments (up to the last 5). A linear trend direction is determined: if scores are consistently declining across the recent window, the trend is flagged as "down". The feedback engagement widget is cross-referenced — if the student is also not reviewing teacher feedback, the declining trend is compounded by a broken teaching presence loop.';
