$string['detail_student_rationale_consistency'] = 'Research on distributed practice consistently demonstrates that spacing study and submission efforts over time leads to better retention and deeper understanding than massed practice (cramming). Bjork & Bjork (2011) show that desirable difficulties — including temporal spacing — strengthen long-term memory. Students who cluster their work are not only more likely to produce lower-quality submissions but also less likely to retain what they have learned.';
$string['detail_student_rationale_selfregulation'] = 'Self-regulated learning (SRL) is one of the strongest predictors of academic success. Macfadyen & Dawson (2012) found that grade-checking frequency correlates strongly with final grade (r=.93). However, SRL encompasses more than grade monitoring alone. Zimmerman\'s (2002) SRL framework identifies forethought (planning), performance monitoring, and self-reflection as three interdependent phases. Students who check their grades, review teacher feedback, revisit course materials, and plan their submissions demonstrate a comprehensive self-regulation cycle. A composite score capturing all four behaviours provides a more robust and actionable diagnostic than any single indicator, while still weighting grade monitoring most heavily in line with the empirical evidence.';
$string['detail_student_rationale_streak'] = 'A broken pass streak after sustained success signals a change in the student\'s circumstances or a step up in difficulty that they have not yet adapted to. Research shows that early intervention at the point of failure — before a pattern of failure becomes established — is significantly more effective than waiting. The combination with inconsistent submission spacing is particularly concerning as it suggests the student may be relying on last-minute effort rather than sustained engagement.';
$string['detail_student_rationale_timing'] = 'Research consistently demonstrates that students who submit work early outperform those who submit at or near the deadline. Steel (2007) found that procrastination accounts for significant variance in academic performance. Late submission patterns often indicate poor self-regulation, competing demands, or difficulty with the material. When combined with inconsistent work spacing, it suggests a pattern of avoidance followed by last-minute cramming.';
$string['detail_student_rationale_trend'] = 'A declining grade trend is one of the most reliable early warning indicators of student disengagement. The trajectory matters more than any single grade — research by Macfadyen & Dawson (2010) found that grade trajectory was a stronger predictor of course completion than absolute grade level. When combined with low feedback engagement, the decline is likely to accelerate because the student is missing the targeted guidance needed to correct course.';
